# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bruise
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Diagnosis may involve ultrasonography, computed tomography, and peritoneal lavage, and treatment may involve surgery.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] It is divided into two types, blunt or penetrating, and may involve damage to the abdominal organs.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Injury to the lower chest may cause splenic or liver injuries.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Signs and symptoms are not seen in early days and after some days initial pain is seen.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] People injured in motor vehicle collisions may present with a "seat belt sign", bruising on the abdomen along the site of the lap portion of the safety belt; this sign is associated with a high rate of injury to the abdominal organs.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Seatbelts may also cause abrasions and hematomas; up to 30 percent of people with such signs have associated internal injuries.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Early indications of abdominal trauma include nausea, vomiting, blood in the urine, and fever.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The injury may present with abdominal pain, tenderness, distension, or rigidity to the touch, and bowel sounds may be diminished or absent.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Abdominal guarding is a tensing of the abdominal wall muscles to guard inflamed organs within the abdomen.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Pneumoperitoneum, air or gas in the abdominal cavity, may be an indication of rupture of a hollow organ.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] In penetrating injuries, an evisceration (protrusion of internal organs out of a wound) may be present.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Injuries associated with intra-abdominal trauma include rib fractures, vertebral fractures, pelvic fractures, and injuries to the abdominal wall.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Motor vehicle collisions are a common source of blunt abdominal trauma.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Seat belts reduce the incidence of injuries such as head injury and chest injury, but present a threat to such abdominal organs as the pancreas and the intestines, which may be displaced or compressed against the spinal column.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Children are especially vulnerable to abdominal injury from seat belts, because they have softer abdominal regions and seat belts were not designed to fit them.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] In children, bicycle mishaps are also a common cause of abdominal injury, especially when the abdomen is struck by the handlebars.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Sports injuries can affect abdominal organs such as the spleen and kidneys.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Falls and sports are also frequent mechanisms of abdominal injury in children.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Abdominal injury may result from child abuse and is the second leading cause of child abuse-related death, after traumatic brain injury.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Gunshot wounds, which are higher energy than stab wounds, are usually more damaging than the latter.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Gunshot wounds that penetrate the peritoneum result in significant damage to major intra-abdominal structures in some 90 percent of cases.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Abdominal trauma can be life-threatening because abdominal organs, especially those in the retroperitoneal space, can bleed profusely, and the space can hold a great deal of blood.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Solid abdominal organs, such as the liver and kidneys, bleed profusely when cut or torn, as do major blood vessels such as the aorta and vena cava.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Hollow organs such as the stomach, while not as likely to result in shock from profuse bleeding, present a serious risk of infection, especially if such an injury is not treated promptly.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Gastrointestinal organs such as the bowel can spill their contents into the abdominal cavity.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Hemorrhage and systemic infection are the main causes of deaths that result from abdominal trauma.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] One or more of the intra-abdominal organs may be injured in abdominal trauma.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The characteristics of the injury are determined in part by which organ or organs are injured.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The liver, the most vulnerable abdominal organ to all forms of injury because of its size and location (in the upper right quadrant of the abdomen), is injured in about five percent of all people admitted to a hospital for trauma.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Liver injuries present a serious risk for shock because the liver tissue is delicate and has a large blood supply and capacity.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The liver may be lacerated or contused, and a hematoma may develop.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] It may leak bile, usually without serious consequences.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] If severely injured, the liver may cause exsanguination (bleeding to death), requiring emergency surgery to stop the bleeding.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The spleen is the most common cause of massive bleeding in blunt abdominal trauma to a solid organ.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The spleen is the most commonly injured organ.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] A laceration of the spleen may be associated with hematoma.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Because of the spleen's ability to bleed profusely, a ruptured spleen can be life-threatening, resulting in shock.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] However, unlike the liver, penetrating trauma to the spleen, pancreas and kidneys do not present as much of an immediate threat of shock unless they lacerate a major blood vessel supplying the organs, such as the renal artery.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Fractures of the left lower ribs are associated with spleen lacerations in 20 percent of cases.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The pancreas may be injured in abdominal trauma, for example by laceration or contusion.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Pancreatic injuries, most commonly caused by bicycle accidents (especially by impact with the handlebars) in children and vehicular accidents in adults, usually occur in isolation in children and accompanied by other injuries in adults.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Indications that the pancreas is injured include enlargement and the presence of fluid around the pancreas.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The kidneys may also be injured; they are somewhat but not completely protected by the ribs.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Kidney lacerations and contusions may also occur.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Kidney injury, a common finding in children with blunt abdominal trauma, may be associated with bloody urine.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Kidney lacerations may be associated with urinoma or leakage of urine into the abdomen.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] A *shattered kidney* is one with multiple lacerations and an associated fragmentation of the kidney tissue.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The small intestine takes up a large part of the abdomen and is likely to be damaged in penetrating injury.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Bowel injury may be associated with complications such as infection, abscess, bowel obstruction, and the formation of a fistula.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Ten percent of people with polytrauma who had no signs of abdominal injury did have evidence of such injuries using radiological imaging.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Diagnostic techniques used include CT scanning, ultrasound, and X-ray.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] X-ray can help determine the path of a penetrating object and locate any foreign matter left in the wound, but may not be helpful in blunt trauma.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Diagnostic laparoscopy or exploratory laparotomy may also be performed if other diagnostic methods do not yield conclusive results.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Ultrasound can detect fluid such as blood or gastrointestinal contents in the abdominal cavity, and it is a noninvasive procedure and relatively safe.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] CT scanning is the preferred technique for people who are not at immediate risk of shock, but since ultrasound can be performed right in an emergency room, the latter is recommended for people who are not stable enough to move to CT scanning.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] A normal ultrasound does not rule out all injuries.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] People with abdominal trauma frequently need CT scans for other trauma (for example, head or chest CT); in these cases abdominal CT can be performed at the same time without wasting time in patient care.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] CT is able to detect 76% of hollow viscous injuries so people who have negative scans are often observed and rechecked if they deteriorate.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] However, CT has been demonstrated to be useful in screening people with certain forms of abdominal trauma in order to avoid unnecessary laparotomies, which can significantly increase the cost and length of hospitalizations.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] A meta-analysis of CT use in penetrating abdominal traumas demonstrated sensitivity, specificity and accuracy >= 95%, with a PPV of 85% and an NPV of 98%.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Diagnostic peritoneal lavage is a controversial technique but can be used to detect injury to abdominal organs: a catheter is placed in the peritoneal cavity, and if fluid is present, it is aspirated and examined for blood or evidence of organ rupture.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] If this does not reveal evidence of injury, sterile saline is infused into the cavity and evacuated and examined for blood or other material.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] While peritoneal lavage is an accurate way to test for bleeding, it carries a risk of injuring the abdominal organs, may be difficult to perform, and may lead to unnecessary surgery; thus it has largely been replaced by ultrasound in Europe and North America.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Abdominal trauma is divided into blunt and penetrating types.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] While penetrating abdominal trauma (PAT) is usually diagnosed based on clinical signs, diagnosis of blunt abdominal trauma is more likely to be delayed or altogether missed because clinical signs are less obvious.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Blunt injuries predominate in rural areas, while penetrating ones are more frequent in urban settings.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Penetrating trauma is further subdivided into stab wounds and gunshot wounds, which require different methods of treatment.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Abdominal trauma requires urgent medical attention and sometimes requires hospitalization.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The initial treatment involves stabilizing the person enough to ensure adequate airway, breathing, and circulation, and identifying other injuries.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Surgery may be needed to repair injured organs.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Surgical exploration may be necessary for people with penetrating injuries and signs of peritonitis or shock.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Laparotomy is often performed in blunt abdominal trauma, and is urgently required if an abdominal injury causes a large, potentially deadly bleed.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The main goal is to stop any sources of bleeding before moving onto any definitive find and repair any injuries that are found.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Due to the time sensitive nature, this procedure also emphasizes expedience in terms of gaining access and controlling the bleeding, thus favoring a long midline incision.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Intra-abdominal injuries are also frequently successfully treated nonoperatively as there is little benefit shown if there is no known active bleeding or potential for infection.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The use of CT scanning allows care providers to use less surgery because they can identify injuries that can be managed conservatively and rule out other injuries that would need surgery.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Depending on the injuries, a person may or may not need intensive care.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] For injuries that penetrate the peritoneal cavity (penetrating abdominal trauma), prophylactic (preventative) antibiotics are often administered with the goal of reducing the risk of sepsis and septic complications, including septicaemia, abscesses in the abdomen, and wound infections.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The effectiveness of the use of antibiotics prophylactically for penetrating abdominal trauma has not been well studied and there is no strong evidence to support one particular antibiotic type or dose over another.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] The length of time that these antibiotics should be used for is also not clear.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] If abdominal injury is not diagnosed promptly, a worse outcome is associated.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Delayed treatment is associated with an especially high morbidity and mortality if perforation of the gastrointestinal tract is involved.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] In the United Kingdom, abdominal trauma due to road traffic accidents and assaults are most common.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] This situation is reversed in South Africa and United States where firearms related trauma are the most common.
[src:bruise/abdominal-trauma] Most deaths resulting from abdominal trauma are preventable; abdominal trauma is one of the most common causes of preventable, trauma-related deaths.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] An **abrasion** is a partial thickness wound caused by damage to the skin.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] It can be superficial, which involves only the epidermis, or deep, which involves the deep dermis.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] Abrasions usually involve minimal bleeding.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] Mild abrasions, also known as *grazes* or *scrapes*, do not scar or bleed because the dermis is left intact, but deep abrasions that disrupt the normal dermal structures may lead to the formation of scar tissue.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] A more traumatic abrasion that removes all layers of skin is called an avulsion.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] Abrasion injuries most commonly occur when exposed skin comes into moving contact with a rough surface, causing a grinding or rubbing away of the upper layers of the epidermis.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] The abrasion should be cleaned and any debris removed.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] A topical antibiotic (such as neomycin or bacitracin) should be applied to prevent infection and to keep the wound moist.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] Dressing the wound is beneficial because it helps keep the wound from drying out, providing a moist environment conducive for healing.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] If the abrasion is painful, a topical analgesic (such as lidocaine or benzocaine) can be applied, but for large abrasions, a systemic analgesic may be necessary.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] Avoid exposing abraded skin to the sun as permanent hyperpigmentation can develop.
[src:bruise/abrasion-medical] The gallery below shows the healing process for an abrasion on the palm caused by sliding on concrete.
[src:bruise/acceleration] In physics, **acceleration** is a measure of how fast and in what direction an object's speed and direction of motion are changing.
[src:bruise/acceleration] It is defined as the rate of change of the velocity.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Like velocity, acceleration has a magnitude and a direction, making it a vector quantity.
[src:bruise/acceleration] The SI unit for acceleration is metre per second squared (m⋅s−2, m/s2).
[src:bruise/acceleration] The **tangential acceleration** of an object is the component of the **acceleration** which is in the same direction as the motion (or tangential velocity) of the object.
[src:bruise/acceleration] When the velocity of the object does not change direction, this is called **linear acceleration**.
[src:bruise/acceleration] **Deceleration** or **retardation**, on the other hand, is the component of the acceleration in the opposite (or antiparallel) direction to the tangential velocity.
[src:bruise/acceleration] **Radial acceleration** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motions) is the component of the acceleration that changes the direction of the object's velocity.
[src:bruise/acceleration] In Newtonian mechanics, the acceleration of a mass arises from forces acting on it, with its *net* acceleration being a result of the *net* force acting on it.
[src:bruise/acceleration] By Newton's second law, the magnitude of the *net* acceleration will be proportional to the magnitude of the *net* force acting on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object, while the direction of the *net* acceleration will be the same as the direction of the *net* force.
[src:bruise/acceleration] An object's average acceleration ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}$ over a period of time is its change in velocity, $\Delta \mathbf {v}$ , divided by the duration of the period, $\Delta t$ .
[src:bruise/acceleration] Mathematically, ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}={\frac {\Delta \mathbf {v} }{\Delta t}}.$ The average acceleration is the simplest way to measure acceleration, requiring only knowledge of the change in velocity and the change in time.
[src:bruise/acceleration] In a strict sense, the average acceleration is the only *true* acceleration one is able to directly measure without appealing to an empirical law, meaning that it is the most fundamental form of acceleration measurement.
[src:bruise/acceleration] The average acceleration is most often used to approximate the kinematics of an object by assuming that the velocity changes linearly with time.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Instantaneous acceleration is the limit of the average acceleration over an infinitesimal interval of time.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Acceleration has the dimensions of velocity (L/T) divided by time, i.e.
[src:bruise/acceleration] The SI unit of acceleration is the metre per second squared (m s−2); or "metre per second per second", as the velocity in metres per second changes by the acceleration value, every second.
[src:bruise/acceleration] An object moving in a circular motion—such as a satellite orbiting the Earth—is accelerating due to the change of direction of motion, although its speed may be constant.
[src:bruise/acceleration] In this case it is said to be undergoing *centripetal* (directed towards the center) acceleration.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Proper acceleration, the acceleration of a body relative to a free-fall condition, is measured by an instrument called an accelerometer.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Newton's second law is normally applied in an inertial reference frame.
[src:bruise/acceleration] In a reference frame accelerating with acceleration a (in one dimension), Newton's laws can still be used by introducing an inertial force (fictitious force) $F=-ma$ on a mass m , opposite the acceleration of the frame.
[src:bruise/acceleration] This accounts for the tendency of the mass to maintain its inertial motion—to stay "as is," at rest or moving at constant velocity—while the frame accelerates.
[src:bruise/acceleration] One example is that a person in an elevator feels heavier or lighter as the elevator accelerates or decelerates.
[src:bruise/acceleration] If m is known, measurement of the supporting force on the mass can be used to infer the acceleration; this is the principle of a mechanical accelerometer.
[src:bruise/acceleration] In general relativity, gravity and inertial acceleration may be locally indistinguishable (see General relativity).
[src:bruise/acceleration] As speeds approach the speed of light, relativistic effects become increasingly large.
[src:bruise/acceleration] When a vehicle starts from a standstill (zero velocity, in an inertial frame of reference) and travels in a straight line at increasing speeds, it is accelerating in the direction of travel.
[src:bruise/acceleration] If the vehicle turns, an acceleration occurs toward the new direction and changes its motion vector.
[src:bruise/acceleration] The component of acceleration of the vehicle in the direction of its velocity is called a **linear acceleration** or **tangential acceleration**, its effect being the passengers on board experience as a fictitious force pushing them back into or away from their seats.
[src:bruise/acceleration] When changing direction, the component of the acceleration perpendicular to the velocity is called **radial** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motion), the reaction to which the passengers experience as a centrifugal force (another fictitious force).
[src:bruise/acceleration] If the speed of the vehicle decreases, this is an acceleration in the opposite direction of the velocity vector, sometimes called **deceleration** or **retardation**, and passengers experience the reaction to deceleration as an inertial force pushing them forward.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Such deceleration is often achieved by retrorocket burning in spacecraft.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Both acceleration and deceleration are treated the same, as they are both changes in velocity.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Each of these accelerations (tangential, radial, deceleration) is felt by passengers until their relative (differential) velocity is neutralised in reference to the acceleration due to change in speed.
[src:bruise/acceleration] where **u**n is the unit (inward) normal vector to the particle's trajectory (also called *the principal normal*), and **r** is its instantaneous radius of curvature based upon the osculating circle at time t.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Geometrical analysis of three-dimensional space curves, which explains tangent, (principal) normal and binormal, is described by the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:bruise/acceleration] A frequently cited example of uniform acceleration is that of an object in free fall in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:bruise/acceleration] The acceleration of a falling body in the absence of resistances to motion is dependent only on the gravitational field strength g (also called *acceleration due to gravity*).
[src:bruise/acceleration] In particular, the motion can be resolved into two orthogonal parts, one of constant velocity and the other according to the above equations.
[src:bruise/acceleration] As Galileo showed, the net result is parabolic motion, which describes, e.g., the trajectory of a projectile in vacuum near the surface of Earth.
[src:bruise/acceleration] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:bruise/acceleration] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:bruise/acceleration] plane in a point of an arbitrary curve in any higher dimension.
[src:bruise/acceleration] In uniform circular motion, that is moving with constant *speed* along a circular path, a particle experiences an acceleration resulting from the change of the direction of the velocity vector, while its magnitude remains constant.
[src:bruise/acceleration] The derivative of the location of a point on a curve with respect to time, i.e. its velocity, turns out to be always exactly tangential to the curve, respectively orthogonal to the radius in this point.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Since in uniform motion the velocity in the tangential direction does not change, the acceleration must be in radial direction, pointing to the center of the circle.
[src:bruise/acceleration] This acceleration constantly changes the direction of the velocity to be tangent in the neighbouring point, thereby rotating the velocity vector along the circle.
[src:bruise/acceleration] This acceleration and the mass of the particle determine the necessary centripetal force, directed *toward* the centre of the circle, as the net force acting on this particle to keep it in this uniform circular motion.
[src:bruise/acceleration] The so-called 'centrifugal force', appearing to act outward on the body, is a so-called pseudo force experienced in the frame of reference of the body in circular motion, due to the body's linear momentum, a vector tangent to the circle of motion.
[src:bruise/acceleration] The tangential component is given by the angular acceleration $\alpha$ , i.e., the rate of change $\alpha ={\dot {\omega }}$ of the angular speed $\omega$ times the radius r .
[src:bruise/acceleration] The sign of the tangential component of the acceleration is determined by the sign of the angular acceleration ( $\alpha$ ), and the tangent is always directed at right angles to the radius vector.
[src:bruise/acceleration] In multi-dimensional Cartesian coordinate systems, acceleration is broken up into components that correspond with each dimensional axis of the coordinate system.
[src:bruise/acceleration] The special theory of relativity describes the behaviour of objects travelling relative to other objects at speeds approaching that of light in vacuum.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Newtonian mechanics is exactly revealed to be an approximation to reality, valid to great accuracy at lower speeds.
[src:bruise/acceleration] As the relevant speeds increase toward the speed of light, acceleration no longer follows classical equations.
[src:bruise/acceleration] As speeds approach that of light, the acceleration produced by a given force decreases, becoming infinitesimally small as light speed is approached; an object with mass can approach this speed asymptotically, but never reach it.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Unless the state of motion of an object is known, it is impossible to distinguish whether an observed force is due to gravity or to acceleration—gravity and inertial acceleration have identical effects.
[src:bruise/acceleration] Albert Einstein called this the equivalence principle, and said that only observers who feel no force at all—including the force of gravity—are justified in concluding that they are not accelerating.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] An estimated 64 percent of patients with venous thromboembolism may have APC resistance.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] The disorder can be acquired or inherited, the hereditary form having an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] APC (with protein S as a cofactor) degrades Factor Va and Factor VIIIa.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] APC resistance is the inability of protein C to cleave Factor Va and/or Factor VIIIa, which allows for longer duration of thrombin generation and may lead to a hypercoagulable state.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] The best known and most common hereditary form is Factor V Leiden, which is responsible for more than 95% of cases.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] Other genetic causes include Factor V Cambridge (VThr306) and the factor V HR2 haplotype (A4070G mutation).
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] Acquired forms of APC resistance occur in the presence of elevated Factor VIII concentrations.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] Antiphospholipid antibodies, pregnancy, and certain forms of estrogen therapy, such as ethinylestradiol-containing birth control pills, have been found to produce acquired APC resistance.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] APC resistance can be evaluated using an APC resistance test.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] There are two types of APC resistance tests with different properties: the activated partial thromboplastin (aPTT)-based test and the endogenous thrombin potential (ETP)-based test.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] Asymptomatic individuals with APC resistance (e.g., heterozygous factor V Leiden) are not normally treated unless additional risk factors for thrombosis are also present.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] An example is surgery, in which perioperative short-term anticoagulation may be used.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] However, people with homozygous factor V Leiden, and people with heterozygous factor V Leiden who have an additional thrombophilic condition (e.g., antithrombin deficiency, protein C deficiency, or protein S deficiency), should be considered for lifelong oral anticoagulation therapy.
[src:bruise/activated-protein-c-resistance] People with APC resistance and initial DVT are treated with a standard anticoagulant regimen, for instance intravenous heparin therapy followed by oral anticoagulation.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] An **aerosol frostbite of the skin** is an injury to the body caused by the pressurized gas within an aerosol spray cooling quickly, with the sudden drop in temperature sufficient to cause frostbite to the applied area.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Medical studies have noted an increase of this practice, known as "frosting", in pediatric and teenage patients.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Adiabatic expansion and/or evaporative cooling (with a low boiling temperature) causes the gas to rapidly cool on exit from the aerosol applier.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] In freeze sprays, a controlled amount of this cooling is useful.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Uncontrolled cooling, however, can result in freeze burns to the skin.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] According to controlled laboratory experiments, the gas from a typical deodorant spray can is able to reduce skin temperature by up to sixty degrees Celsius.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] The form of injury is freezing of the skin, a type of frostbite.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] It is highly advised for those who develop frostbite to seek medical attention.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] In rare cases aerosol-induced burns can be severe enough to necessitate skin grafting.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Depending on the duration of exposure aerosol-induced frostbite can vary in depth.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Most injuries of this type only affect the epidermis, the outermost layer of skin.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] However, if contact with the aerosol is prolonged the skin will freeze further and deeper layers of tissue will be affected, causing a more serious burn that reaches the dermis, destroys nerves, and increases the risk of infection and scarring.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] When the skin thaws, pain and severe discomfort can occur in the affected area.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] There may be a smell of aerosol products such as deodorant around the affected area, the injury may itch or be painful, the skin may freeze and become hardened, blisters may form on the area, and the flesh can become red and swollen.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] The most common cause of aerosol burns is patients' spraying deodorants for prolonged periods of time in close proximity to their skin.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] This practice is more common in younger persons such as teenagers and can be referred to as "frosting" or having a "frosty".
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Injuries such as these are often self-inflicted, and depression should be considered as an underlying cause.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] However, some do it for social media attention in viral video posts or after peer pressure, the "Deodorant Challenge" being analogous to the Cinnamon challenge and Tide Pod challenge.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] However, some do it due to influence by their peers as a way of "impressing" them, with the "Aerosol Challenge" gaining popularity alongside the "Cinnamon Challenge" and "Chubby Bunny" contests as trends in dangerous peer-pressure-induced self-harm.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] A person can cause frostbite by accidental prolonged contact, using an aerosol on one place for too long.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] This is often done with deodorants, but other products such as asthma inhalers are also common causes of injury.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Injuries are especially common with younger children who "try it out" not knowing all the possible dermatological effects.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] In rarer cases aerosol burns are reported to have been caused by air fresheners and other compressed aerosol canisters exploding.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Fluorinated hydrocarbon (fluorocarbon) aerosol propellants can be abused, as with solvents.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] A common form is huffing as a means of intoxication.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] When inhaled, aerosols can cause the same frostbite as on other parts of the body.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] The National Institute on Drug Abuse (NIDA) has published various resources on the internet warning of the effects of this abuse.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Some aerosol burns are intentionally self-inflicted, the reasons being emotional/psychological.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Household aerosol products such as air fresheners and deodorants can be a convenient, easily available means to satisfy the compulsions.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] Various methods of treatment are used, depending greatly on the length of exposure and other factors.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] There are documented cases using both conservative and invasive treatments, including skin grafting and/or the application of nonadhesive dressing alongside topical corticosteroids to reduce inflammation.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] However, the use of steroids may exacerbate fungal infections if the aerosol product used is an antifungal medicine.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] In some patients postinflammatory hypopigmentation or hyperpigmentation may result in the months after initial injury, and ultraviolet protection such as sunscreen is essential to prevent an elevated risk of skin cancer in the damaged tissues.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] The pain caused by these burns is often intense and can be prolonged, making a pain management plan important.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] This often includes short term prescriptions of painkillers.
[src:bruise/aerosol-burn] In the case of self-harm induced injury the underlying mental health aspects should be treated as with all self-inflicted injuries.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] An **allergy** is an exaggerated immune response where the body mistakenly identifies an ordinarily harmless allergen as a threat.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergic reactions give rise to **allergic diseases** such as hay fever, allergic conjunctivitis, allergic asthma, atopic dermatitis, food allergies, and anaphylaxis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Symptoms of allergic diseases may include red eyes, an itchy rash, sneezing, coughing, a runny nose, shortness of breath, or swelling.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Common allergens include pollen, certain foods, metals, insect stings, medications, and materials, such as latex.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The development of allergies is due to genetic and environmental factors.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The mechanism of allergic reactions involves immunoglobulin E antibodies (IgE) binding to an allergen and then to a receptor on mast cells or basophils, where they trigger the release of inflammatory chemicals such as histamine.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Diagnosis is typically based on a person's medical history.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Further testing of the skin or blood may be useful in certain cases.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Positive tests, however, may not necessarily mean there is a significant allergy to the substance in question.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Early exposure of children to potential allergens may be protective.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Treatments for allergies include avoidance of known allergens and the use of medications such as steroids and antihistamines.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In severe reactions, injectable adrenaline (epinephrine) is recommended.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergen immunotherapy, which gradually exposes people to larger and larger amounts of allergen, is useful for some types of allergies such as hay fever and reactions to insect bites.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In the developed world, about 20% of people are affected by allergic rhinitis, food allergy affects 10% of adults and 8% of children, and about 20% have or have had atopic dermatitis at some point in time.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Depending on the country, about 1–18% of people have asthma.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Anaphylaxis occurs in between 0.05–2% of people.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Rates of many allergic diseases appear to be increasing.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The word "allergy" was first used by Clemens von Pirquet in 1906.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Many allergens, such as dust or pollen, are airborne particles.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In these cases, symptoms arise in areas exposed to air, such as the eyes, nose, and lungs.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] For instance, allergic rhinitis, also known as hay fever, irritates the nose, sneezing, itching, and redness of the eyes.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Inhaled allergens can also lead to increased production of mucus in the lungs, shortness of breath, coughing, and wheezing.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergic rhinitis can simultaneously occur with other allergic responses such as asthma.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Aside from these ambient allergens, allergic reactions can result from foods, insect stings, and reactions to medications like aspirin and antibiotics such as penicillin.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Symptoms of food allergy include abdominal pain, bloating, vomiting, diarrhea, itchy skin, and hives.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Food allergies rarely cause respiratory (asthmatic) reactions, or rhinitis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Insect stings, food, antibiotics, and certain medicines may produce a systemic allergic response that is also called anaphylaxis; multiple organ systems can be affected, including the digestive system, the respiratory system, and the circulatory system.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Depending on the severity, anaphylaxis can include skin reactions, bronchoconstriction, swelling, low blood pressure, coma, and death.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This type of reaction can be triggered suddenly or have a delayed onset.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The anaphylactic reaction may seem to subside, but may recur over time.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Substances that come into contact with the skin, such as latex, are also common causes of allergic reactions, known as contact dermatitis or eczema.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Skin allergies frequently cause rashes, or swelling and inflammation within the skin, in what is known as a "wheal and flare" reaction characteristic of hives and angioedema.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] With insect stings, a large local reaction may occur as an area of skin redness greater than 10 cm in size that can last one to two days.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This reaction may also occur after immunotherapy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The skin forms an effective barrier to the entry of most allergens, but this barrier cannot withstand everything.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] For example, an insect sting can breach the barrier and inject allergen into the affected spot.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] When an allergen enters the epidermis or dermis, it triggers a localized allergic reaction which activates the mast cells in the skin resulting in an immediate increase in permeability of blood vessels, leading to fluid leakage and swelling in the affected area.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Mast-cell activation also stimulates a skin lesion called the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Then the release of chemicals from local nerve endings by a nerve axon reflex causes the widening of surrounding cutaneous blood vessels, which causes redness of the surrounding skin.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] As part of the allergic response, the body has developed a secondary response that, in some individuals, causes a more widespread and sustained skin swelling.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This usually occurs about 8 hours after the allergen originally comes in contact with the skin.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] When an allergen is ingested, a dispersed form of wheal-and-flare reaction, known as urticaria or hives, will appear when the allergen enters the bloodstream and eventually reaches the skin.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This same skin reactivity allows allergists to test for existing allergies by injecting a small amount of an allergen into the skin, which causes a reaction at the injection site.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Even though these injections are very small and local, they still pose the risk of causing systemic anaphylaxis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Substances that come into contact with the airways may trigger allergic reactions in the nose, sinuses, throat and lungs.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergic rhinitis, often referred to as hay fever, is one of the most common airway allergies and is characterized by sneezing, nasal congestion, rhinorrhea and itching of the nose and eyes.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Airborne allergens commonly associated with allergic rhinitis include pollen, house dust mites, animal dander and mold spores.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergic reactions involving the lower airways may contribute to allergic asthma, in which exposure to allergens can lead to bronchoconstriction, wheezing, coughing and shortness of breath.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Common triggers include pollen, dust mites, animal allergens and occupational exposures such as flour dust or chemical sensitizers.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Some allergic airway reactions may occur rapidly after exposure, while others develop over several hours.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Severe reactions involving airway swelling may impair breathing and constitute a medical emergency.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) is responsible for distinguishing pathogenic organisms from harmless food proteins and commensal bacteria.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Antigens sampled across the intestinal epithelium are presented by CD103+ dendritic cells, which migrate to mesenteric lymph nodes and promote differentiation of Foxp3+ regulatory T cells (Tregs).
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] These Tregs subsequently return to the intestinal lamina propria, where cytokines such as interleukin-10 and transforming growth factor-β (TGF-β) contribute to the maintenance of immune tolerance and suppression of allergic T helper 2 (Th2) responses.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Disruption of these regulatory pathways may contribute to allergic sensitization and the development of food allergy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Impairment of the intestinal epithelial barrier, altered antigen processing, inflammation, or reduced regulatory T-cell activity may shift immune responses toward IgE-mediated hypersensitivity.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Such defects in oral tolerance have been associated with increased Th2 polarization, elevated allergen-specific IgE production, and reduced regulatory immune activity.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Environmental and dietary factors, including vitamin D deficiency, infections, antibiotic exposure, and changes in food processing, may also influence allergy development through their effects on gut immunity and epithelial integrity.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The intestinal microbiome is increasingly recognized as an important factor in allergy development.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Early-life alterations in the composition and diversity of the intestinal microbiota have been associated with an increased risk of food allergy and atopic disease.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Commensal bacteria contribute to immune maturation, maintenance of epithelial barrier function, and induction of tolerogenic immune responses.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Reduced microbial diversity and loss of certain bacterial taxa may impair oral tolerance and promote allergic sensitization.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Short-chain fatty acids produced by intestinal bacteria may further support regulatory immune pathways and intestinal barrier integrity.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Sensitization to food allergens may also occur through non-oral routes.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Exposure to allergens through damaged skin, particularly in individuals with impaired skin barriers such as those with atopic dermatitis, may predispose to food allergy if oral tolerance has not yet been established.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This has contributed to the hypothesis that the timing, route, and context of allergen exposure influence whether tolerance or allergic sensitization develops.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Research into gastrointestinal immune mechanisms has influenced preventive approaches to food allergy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Early introduction of allergenic foods, including peanuts and eggs, during infancy has been associated in some populations with a reduced risk of food allergy, likely by promoting oral tolerance during critical periods of immune development.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Risk factors for allergies can be placed in two broad categories: host and environmental factors.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Host factors include heredity, sex, race, and age, with heredity being by far the most significant.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] However, there has been a recent increase in the incidence of allergic disorders that cannot be explained by genetic factors alone.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Four major environmental candidates are alterations in exposure to infectious diseases during early childhood, environmental pollution, allergen levels, and dietary changes.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Dust mite allergy, also known as house dust allergy, is a sensitization and allergic reaction to the droppings of house dust mites.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The allergy is common and can trigger allergic reactions such as asthma, eczema, or itching.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The mite's gut contains potent digestive enzymes (notably peptidase 1) that persist in their faeces and are major inducers of allergic reactions such as wheezing.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The mite's exoskeleton can also contribute to allergic reactions.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Unlike scabies mites or skin follicle mites, house dust mites do not burrow under the skin and are not parasitic.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Dust mite-proof encasements to mattress, pillow, and duvet prevent chronic contact with allergens.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] A wide variety of foods can cause allergic reactions, but 90% of allergic responses to foods are caused by cow's milk, soy, eggs, wheat, peanuts, tree nuts, fish, and shellfish.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Other food allergies, affecting less than 1 person per 10,000 population, may be considered "rare".
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The most common food allergy in the US population is a sensitivity to crustacea.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Although peanut allergies are notorious for their severity, peanut allergies are not the most common food allergy in adults or children.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Other allergens may trigger severe or life-threatening reactions and are more common when combined with asthma.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Rates of allergies differ between adults and children.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Children can sometimes outgrow peanut allergies.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Egg allergies affect one to two percent of children but are outgrown by about two-thirds of children by the age of 5.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The sensitivity is usually to proteins in the white, rather than the yolk.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Milk-protein allergies—distinct from lactose intolerance—are most common in children.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Approximately 60% of milk-protein reactions are immunoglobulin E–mediated, with the remaining usually attributable to inflammation of the colon.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Some people are unable to tolerate milk from goats or sheep as well as from cows, and many are also unable to tolerate dairy products such as cheese.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Roughly 10% of children with a milk allergy will have a reaction to beef.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Lactose intolerance, a common reaction to milk, is not a form of allergy at all, but due to the absence of an enzyme in the digestive tract.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Those with tree nut allergies may be allergic to one or many tree nuts, including pecans, pistachios, and walnuts.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In addition, seeds, including sesame seeds and poppy seeds, contain oils in which protein is present, which may elicit an allergic reaction.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergens can be transferred from one food to another through genetic engineering; however, genetic modification can also remove allergens.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Little research has been done on the natural variation of allergen concentrations in unmodified crops.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Latex can trigger an IgE-mediated cutaneous, respiratory, and systemic reaction.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The prevalence of latex allergy in the general population is believed to be less than one percent.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In a hospital study, 1 in 800 surgical patients (0.125 percent) reported latex sensitivity, although the sensitivity among healthcare workers is higher, between seven and ten percent.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Researchers attribute this higher level to the exposure of healthcare workers to areas with significant airborne latex allergens, such as operating rooms, intensive-care units, and dental suites.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] These latex-rich environments may sensitize healthcare workers who regularly inhale allergenic proteins.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The most prevalent response to latex is allergic contact dermatitis, a delayed hypersensitivity reaction that manifests as dry, crusted lesions.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This reaction usually lasts 48–96 hours.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Sweating or rubbing the area under the glove aggravates the lesions, possibly leading to ulcerations.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Anaphylactic reactions occur most often in sensitive patients who have been exposed to a surgeon's latex gloves during abdominal surgery, but other mucosal exposures, such as dental procedures, can also produce systemic reactions.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Latex and banana sensitivity may cross-react.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Furthermore, those with latex allergy may also have sensitivities to avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] These people often have perioral itching and local urticaria.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Only occasionally have these food-induced allergies induced systemic responses.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Researchers suspect that the cross-reactivity of latex with banana, avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut occurs because latex proteins are structurally homologous with some other plant proteins.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] About 10% of people report that they are allergic to penicillin; however, of that 10%, 90% turn out not to be.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Serious allergies only occur in about 0.03%.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] One of the main sources of human allergies is insects.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Insect bites, stings, ingestion, and inhalation can trigger an insect allergy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Another non-food protein reaction, urushiol-induced contact dermatitis, originates after contact with poison ivy, eastern poison oak, western poison oak, or poison sumac.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Urushiol, which is not itself a protein, acts as a hapten and chemically reacts with, binds to, and changes the shape of integral membrane proteins on exposed skin cells.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The immune system does not recognize the affected cells as normal parts of the body, causing a T-cell-mediated immune response.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Of these poisonous plants, sumac is the most virulent.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The resulting dermatological response to the reaction between urushiol and membrane proteins includes redness, swelling, papules, vesicles, blisters, and streaking.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Estimates vary on the fraction of the population that will have an immune system response.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Approximately 25% of the population will have a strong allergic response to urushiol.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In general, approximately 80–90% of adults will develop a rash if they are exposed to 0.0050 mg (7.7×10−5 gr) of purified urushiol.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Some people are so sensitive that a molecular trace on the skin can initiate an allergic reaction.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergic diseases are strongly familial; identical twins are likely to have the same allergic diseases about 70% of the time; the same allergy occurs about 40% of the time in non-identical twins.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergic parents are more likely to have allergic children and those children's allergies are likely to be more severe than those in children of non-allergic parents.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Some allergies, however, are not consistent along genealogies; parents who are allergic to peanuts may have children who are allergic to ragweed.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The likelihood of developing allergies is inherited and related to an irregularity in the immune system, but the specific allergen is not.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The risk of allergic sensitization and the development of allergies varies with age, with young children most at risk.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Several studies have shown that IgE levels are highest in childhood and fall rapidly between the ages of 10 and 30 years.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The peak prevalence of hay fever is highest in children and young adults, and the incidence of asthma is highest in children under 10.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Ethnicity may play a role in some allergies; however, racial factors have been difficult to separate from environmental influences and changes due to migration.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] It has been suggested that different genetic loci are responsible for asthma, to be specific, in people of European, Hispanic, Asian, and African origins.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Some loci, such as PRDM2 and POU2AF1, showed pleiotropic effects linking allergic and autoimmune conditions, suggesting shared inflammatory pathways across epithelial tissues.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Within atopic airway disease specifically, the same review noted that IL-13—produced mainly by activated TH2 cells—is a key driver of eosinophilic airway inflammation and remodeling, acting partly through pathways independent of IgE and eosinophils.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergic diseases are caused by inappropriate immunological responses to harmless antigens driven by a TH2-mediated immune response.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Many bacteria and viruses elicit a TH1-mediated immune response, which down-regulates TH2 responses.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The first proposed mechanism of action of the hygiene hypothesis was that insufficient stimulation of the TH1 arm of the immune system leads to an overactive TH2 arm, which in turn leads to allergic disease.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In other words, individuals living in too sterile an environment are not exposed to enough pathogens to keep the immune system busy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Since our bodies evolved to deal with a certain level of such pathogens, when they are not exposed to this level, the immune system will attack harmless antigens.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Thus, normally benign microbial objects—like pollen—will trigger an immune response.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] It is used to explain the increase in allergic diseases that have been seen since industrialization, and the higher incidence of allergic diseases in more developed countries.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The hygiene hypothesis has now expanded to include exposure to symbiotic bacteria and parasites as important modulators of immune system development, along with infectious agents.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Epidemiological data support the hygiene hypothesis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Longitudinal studies in the third world demonstrate an increase in immunological disorders as a country grows more affluent and, it is presumed, cleaner.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The use of antibiotics in the first year of life has been linked to asthma and other allergic diseases.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The use of antibacterial cleaning products has also been associated with a higher incidence of asthma, as has birth by caesarean section rather than vaginal birth.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Chronic stress can aggravate allergic conditions.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This has been attributed to a T helper 2 (TH2)-predominant response driven by suppression of interleukin 12 by both the autonomic nervous system and the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Stress management in highly susceptible individuals may improve symptoms.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergic diseases are more common in industrialized countries than in countries that are more traditional or agricultural, and there is a higher rate of allergic disease in urban populations versus rural populations, although these differences are becoming less defined.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Historically, the trees planted in urban areas were predominantly male to prevent litter from seeds and fruits, but the high ratio of male trees causes high pollen counts, a phenomenon that horticulturist Tom Ogren has called "botanical sexism".
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Alterations in exposure to microorganisms is another plausible explanation, at present, for the increase in atopic allergy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Endotoxin exposure reduces release of inflammatory cytokines such as TNF-α, IFNγ, interleukin-10, and interleukin-12 from white blood cells (leukocytes) that circulate in the blood.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Certain microbe-sensing proteins, known as Toll-like receptors, found on the surface of cells in the body, are also thought to be involved in these processes.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Parasitic worms and similar parasites are present in untreated drinking water in developing countries, and were present in the water of developed countries until the routine chlorination and purification of drinking water supplies.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Recent research has shown that some common parasites, such as intestinal worms (e.g., hookworms), secrete chemicals into the gut wall (and, hence, the bloodstream) that suppress the immune system and prevent the body from attacking the parasite.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This gives rise to a new slant on the hygiene hypothesis theory—that co-evolution of humans and parasites has led to an immune system that functions correctly only in the presence of the parasites.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Without them, the immune system becomes unbalanced and oversensitive.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In particular, research suggests that allergies may coincide with the delayed establishment of gut flora in infants.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] However, the research to support this theory is conflicting, with some studies performed in China and Ethiopia showing an increase in allergy in people infected with intestinal worms.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Clinical trials have been initiated to test the effectiveness of helminthic therapy with certain worms in treating some allergies.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] It may be that the term 'parasite' could turn out to be inappropriate, and in fact a hitherto unsuspected symbiosis is at work.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] These TH2 cells interact with other lymphocytes called B cells, whose role is the production of antibodies.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Coupled with signals provided by IL-4, this interaction stimulates the B cell to begin production of a large amount of a particular type of antibody known as IgE.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Secreted IgE circulates in the blood and binds to an IgE-specific receptor (a kind of Fc receptor called FcεRI) on the surface of other kinds of immune cells called mast cells and basophils, which are both involved in the acute inflammatory response.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] At this stage, the IgE-coated cells are sensitized to the allergen.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] If later exposure to the same allergen occurs, the allergen can bind to IgE molecules held on the surface of the mast cells or basophils.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Cross-linking of the IgE and Fc receptors occurs when more than one IgE-receptor complex interacts with the same allergenic molecule and activates the sensitized cell.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This results in rhinorrhea, itchiness, dyspnea, and anaphylaxis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Depending on the individual, allergen, and mode of introduction, the symptoms can be system-wide (classical anaphylaxis) or localized to specific body systems.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Asthma is localized to the respiratory system, and eczema is localized to the dermis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] After the chemical mediators of the acute response subside, late-phase responses can often occur.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This is due to the migration of other leukocytes such as neutrophils, lymphocytes, eosinophils, and macrophages to the initial site.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The reaction is usually seen 2–24 hours after the original reaction.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Cytokines from mast cells may play a role in the persistence of long-term effects.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Late-phase responses in asthma differ slightly from those seen in other allergic responses.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] They are still caused by the release of mediators from eosinophils and remain dependent on TH2 cell activity.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Although allergic contact dermatitis is termed an "allergic" reaction (which usually refers to type I hypersensitivity), its pathophysiology involves a reaction that more correctly corresponds to a type IV hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In type IV hypersensitivity, there is activation of certain types of T cells (CD8+) that destroy target cells on contact, as well as activated macrophages that produce hydrolytic enzymes.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Effective management of allergic diseases relies on the ability to make an accurate diagnosis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergy testing can help confirm or rule out allergies.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Correct diagnosis, counseling, and avoidance advice based on valid allergy test results reduce the incidence of symptoms and need for medications, and improve quality of life.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] To assess the presence of allergen-specific IgE antibodies, two different methods can be used: a skin prick test or an allergy blood test.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Both methods are recommended, and they have similar diagnostic value.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Skin prick tests and blood tests are equally cost-effective, and health economic evidence shows that both tests are cost-effective compared with no test.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Early and more accurate diagnoses save costs due to reduced consultations, referrals to secondary care, misdiagnosis, and emergency admissions.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergy undergoes dynamic changes over time.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Regular allergy testing of relevant allergens provides information on if and how patient management can be changed to improve health and quality of life.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Annual testing is often the practice for determining whether allergy to milk, egg, soy, and wheat have been outgrown, and the testing interval is extended to 2–3 years for allergy to peanut, tree nuts, fish, and crustacean shellfish.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Results of follow-up testing can guide decision-making regarding whether and when it is safe to introduce or re-introduce allergenic food into the diet.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Skin testing is also known as "puncture testing" and "prick testing" since it involves a series of tiny punctures or pricks being placed into the patient's skin.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Tiny amounts of suspected allergens and/or their extracts (*e.g.*, pollen, grass, mite proteins, peanut extract) are introduced to sites on the skin marked with pen or dye (the ink/dye should be carefully selected, lest it cause an allergic response itself).
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] A negative and positive control are also included for comparison (e.g., negative is saline or glycerin; positive is histamine).
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] A small plastic or metal device is used to puncture or prick the skin.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Sometimes, allergens are injected "intradermally" into the patient's skin, with a needle and syringe.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Common areas for testing include the inside of the forearm and the back.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] If the patient is allergic to the substance, then a visible inflammatory reaction will usually occur within 30 minutes.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] This response ranges from slight reddening of the skin to a full-blown hive (called "wheal and flare") in more sensitive patients, similar to a mosquito bite.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Interpretation of the results of the skin prick test is usually done by allergists on a severity scale, with +/− meaning borderline reactivity, and 4+ representing a large reaction.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Increasingly, allergists are measuring and recording the diameter of the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Interpretation by well-trained allergists is often guided by relevant literature.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In general, a positive response is interpreted when the wheal of an antigen is ≥3 mm larger than the wheal of the negative control (e.g., saline or glycerin).
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Some patients may believe they have determined their own allergic sensitivity from observation.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] A skin test is much better than patient observation for allergy detection.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] If a serious life-threatening anaphylactic reaction has brought a patient in for evaluation, some allergists may prefer to perform an initial blood test before conducting a skin prick test.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Skin testing may also not be possible in patients with widespread skin disease or those who have taken antihistamine within the past several days.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Patch testing is a diagnostic method used to identify substances that cause allergic contact dermatitis through a delayed hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] During the procedure, small amounts of potential allergens are applied to the skin, usually on the back, using adhesive patches containing standardized allergen preparations.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The patches are typically left in place for 48 hours, after which the skin is examined for localized eczematous reactions.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Additional readings are commonly performed 72–96 hours after application because allergic contact reactions may develop slowly.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Unlike skin prick testing, which is used to diagnose immediate IgE-mediated allergies, patch testing evaluates delayed type IV hypersensitivity reactions mediated by T cells.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergy blood testing, typically measuring allergen-specific IgE, is a quick test that can be ordered by a qualified healthcare professional.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Unlike skin-prick testing, it is not affected by antihistamines and may be used when skin testing is impractical, such as in people with extensive eczema or other skin disease, in pregnancy, or when there is concern about provoking symptoms.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] It can be performed in adults and children, including infants, although results must be interpreted together with the clinical history because sensitisation does not always mean clinical allergy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] An allergy blood test is available through most laboratories.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] A sample of the patient's blood is sent to a laboratory for analysis, and the results are sent back a few days later.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Multiple allergens can be detected with a single blood sample.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergy blood tests are very safe because the person is not exposed to any allergens during the testing procedure.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] After the onset of anaphylaxis or a severe allergic reaction, guidelines recommend that emergency departments obtain a time-sensitive blood test to measure tryptase levels and assess for mast cells activation.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The test measures the concentration of specific IgE antibodies in the blood.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Quantitative IgE test results increase the possibility of ranking how different substances may affect symptoms.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] A rule of thumb is that the higher the IgE antibody value, the greater the likelihood of symptoms.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergens found at low levels that today do not result in symptoms cannot predict future symptom development.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The quantitative allergy blood result can help determine what a patient is allergic to, predict and monitor disease progression, estimate the risk of a severe reaction, and explain cross-reactivity.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] A low total IgE level is not adequate to rule out sensitization to commonly inhaled allergens.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Statistical methods, such as ROC curves, predictive value calculations, and likelihood ratios have been used to examine the relationship of various testing methods to each other.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] These methods have shown that patients with high total IgE have a high probability of allergic sensitization, but further investigation with allergy tests for specific IgE antibodies for a carefully chosen set of allergens is often warranted.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Laboratory methods to measure specific IgE antibodies for allergy testing include enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay, radioallergosorbent test, fluorescent enzyme immunoassay, and chemiluminescence immunoassay.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Before a diagnosis of allergic disease can be confirmed, other plausible causes of the presenting symptoms must be considered.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Vasomotor rhinitis, for example, is one of many illnesses that share symptoms with allergic rhinitis, underscoring the need for professional differential diagnosis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Once a diagnosis of asthma, rhinitis, anaphylaxis, or other allergic disease has been made, there are several methods for discovering the causative agent of that allergy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Giving peanut products early in childhood may decrease the risk of allergies, and only breastfeeding during at least the first few months of life may decrease the risk of allergic dermatitis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] There is little evidence that a mother's diet during pregnancy or breastfeeding affects the risk of allergies, although there has been some research to show that irregular cow's milk exposure might increase the risk of cow's milk allergy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] There is some evidence that delayed introduction of certain foods is useful, and that early exposure to potential allergens may actually be protective.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Following revisions to US and UK pediatric guidelines in 2015 and 2017 that encouraged introducing peanut products to high-risk infants at four to six months of age, one 2025 analysis found a 43% drop in the frequency of peanut allergies, with an estimated 40,000 cases prevented.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] According to that report, some pediatric experts have cautioned that real-world implementation of the guidelines may be inconsistent.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Fish oil supplementation during pregnancy is associated with a lower risk of food sensitivities.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Probiotic supplements during pregnancy or infancy may help to prevent atopic dermatitis.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Management of allergies typically involves avoiding the allergy trigger and taking medications to relieve symptoms.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergen immunotherapy may be useful for some types of allergies.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Several medications may be used to block the actions of allergic mediators, prevent cell activation, and degranulation processes.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] These include antihistamines, glucocorticoids, epinephrine (adrenaline), mast cell stabilizers, and antileukotriene agents are common treatments of allergic diseases.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Anticholinergics, decongestants, and other compounds thought to impair eosinophil chemotaxis are also commonly used.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Although rare, the severity of anaphylaxis often requires epinephrine injection, and where medical care is unavailable, a device known as an epinephrine autoinjector may be used.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Allergen immunotherapy is useful for environmental allergies, allergies to insect bites, and asthma.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Its benefit for food allergies is unclear and thus not recommended.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Immunotherapy involves exposing people to larger and larger amounts of allergen in an effort to change the immune system's response.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Meta-analyses have found that injections of allergens under the skin is effective in the treatment in allergic rhinitis in children and in asthma.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The benefits may last for years after treatment is stopped.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] It is generally safe and effective for allergic rhinitis and conjunctivitis, allergic forms of asthma, and stinging insects.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] To a lesser extent, the evidence also supports the use of sublingual immunotherapy for rhinitis and asthma.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] For seasonal allergies the benefit is small.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In this form the allergen is given under the tongue and people often prefer it to injections.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Immunotherapy is not recommended as a stand-alone treatment for asthma.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] An experimental treatment, enzyme potentiated desensitization (EPD), has been tried for decades but is not generally accepted as effective.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] EPD uses dilutions of allergen and an enzyme, beta-glucuronidase, to which T-regulatory lymphocytes are supposed to respond by favoring desensitization, or down-regulation, rather than sensitization.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] EPD has also been tried for the treatment of autoimmune diseases, but evidence does not show effectiveness.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] A review found no effectiveness of homeopathic treatments and no difference compared with placebo.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The authors concluded that, based on rigorous clinical trials of all types of homeopathy for childhood and adolescent ailments, there is no convincing evidence that supports the use of homeopathic treatments.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The allergic diseases—hay fever and asthma—have increased in the Western world over the past 2–3 decades.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Increases in allergic asthma and other atopic disorders in industrialized nations, it is estimated, began in the 1960s and 1970s, with further increases occurring during the 1980s and 1990s, although some suggest that a steady rise in sensitization has been occurring since the 1920s.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The number of new cases per year of atopy in developing countries has, in general, remained much lower.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Although genetic factors govern susceptibility to atopic disease, increases in atopy have occurred within too short a period to be explained by a genetic change in the population, thus pointing to environmental or lifestyle changes.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Several hypotheses have been identified to explain this increased rate.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Increased exposure to perennial allergens may be due to housing changes and increased time spent indoors, and changes in cleanliness may decrease activation of a common immune control mechanisms or hygiene, and exacerbated by dietary changes, obesity, and decline in physical exercise.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The hygiene hypothesis maintains that high living standards and hygienic conditions expose children to fewer infections.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] It is thought that reduced bacterial and viral infections early in life direct the maturing immune system away from TH1 type responses, leading to unrestrained TH2 responses that allow for an increase in allergy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Changes in rates and types of infection alone, however, have been unable to explain the observed increase in allergic disease, and recent evidence has focused attention on the importance of the gastrointestinal microbial environment.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] It is speculated that these infections exert their effect by critically altering TH1/TH2 regulation.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Important elements of newer hygiene hypotheses also include exposure to endotoxins, exposure to pets and growing up on a farm.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Some symptoms attributable to allergic diseases are mentioned in ancient sources.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Particularly, three members of the Roman Julio-Claudian dynasty (Augustus, Claudius and Britannicus) are suspected to have a family history of atopy.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The concept of "allergy" was originally introduced in 1906 by the Viennese pediatrician Clemens von Pirquet, after he noticed that patients who had received injections of horse serum or smallpox vaccine usually had quicker, more severe reactions to second injections.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Pirquet called this phenomenon "allergy" from the Ancient Greek words ἄλλος *allos* meaning "other" and ἔργον *ergon* meaning "work".
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] All forms of hypersensitivity were previously classified as allergies, and all were thought to be caused by an improper activation of the immune system.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Later, it became clear that several disease mechanisms were implicated, with a common link to disordered immune system activation.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In 1963, a new classification scheme was designed by Philip Gell and Robin Coombs that described four types of hypersensitivity reactions, known as Type I to Type IV hypersensitivity.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] With this new classification, the word *allergy*, sometimes clarified as a *true allergy*, was restricted to type I hypersensitivities (also called immediate hypersensitivity), which are characterized as rapidly developing reactions involving IgE antibodies.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] A breakthrough in understanding the mechanisms of allergy was the discovery of the antibody class labeled immunoglobulin E (IgE).
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] IgE was simultaneously discovered in 1966–67 by two independent groups: Ishizaka's team at the Children's Asthma Research Institute and Hospital in Denver, USA, and by Gunnar Johansson and Hans Bennich in Uppsala, Sweden.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Their joint paper was published in April 1969.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] Radiometric assays include the radioallergosorbent test (RAST test) method, which uses IgE-binding (anti-IgE) antibodies labeled with radioactive isotopes for quantifying the levels of IgE antibody in the blood.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The RAST methodology was invented and marketed in 1974 by Pharmacia Diagnostics AB, Uppsala, Sweden, and the acronym RAST is actually a brand name.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] In 1989, Pharmacia Diagnostics AB replaced it with a superior test named the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, which uses the newer fluorescence-labeled technology.
[src:bruise/allergies-p01] The updated version, the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, is the only specific IgE assay the Food and Drug Administration has approved to quantitatively report to its detection limit of 0.1 kU/L.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] The medical speciality that studies, diagnoses, and treats diseases caused by allergies is called allergology.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] An allergist is a physician specially trained to manage and treat allergies, asthma, and other allergic diseases.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] Becoming an allergist/immunologist requires completion of at least nine years of training.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] After completing medical school and graduating with a medical degree, a physician will undergo three years of training in internal medicine (to become an internist) or pediatrics (to become a pediatrician).
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] Internists or pediatricians wishing to focus on the sub-specialty of allergy-immunology then complete at least an additional two years of study, called a fellowship, in an allergy/immunology training program.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] Allergists/immunologists listed as ABAI-certified have successfully passed the certifying ABAI examination following their fellowship.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] In the United Kingdom, allergy is a subspecialty of general medicine or pediatrics.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] After obtaining postgraduate exams (MRCP or MRCPCH), a doctor works for several years as a specialist registrar before qualifying for the General Medical Council specialist register.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] Allergy services may also be delivered by immunologists.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] A 2003 Royal College of Physicians report presented a case for improvement of what were felt to be inadequate allergy services in the UK.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] In 2006, the House of Lords convened a subcommittee.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] It concluded likewise in 2007 that allergy services were insufficient to deal with what the Lords referred to as an "allergy epidemic" and its social cost; it made several recommendations.
[src:bruise/allergies-p02] Low-allergen foods are being developed, as are improvements in skin prick test predictions; evaluation of the atopy patch test, wasp sting outcomes predictions, a rapidly disintegrating epinephrine tablet, and anti-IL-5 for eosinophilic diseases.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Some alternative practices are based on theories that contradict the established science of how the human body works; others appeal to the supernatural or superstitions to explain their effect or lack thereof.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In others, the practice has plausibility but lacks a positive risk–benefit outcome probability.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Research into alternative therapies often fails to follow proper research protocols (such as placebo-controlled trials, blind experiments and calculation of prior probability), providing invalid results.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] History has shown that if a method is proven to work, it eventually ceases to be alternative and becomes mainstream medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Much of the perceived effect of an alternative practice arises from a belief that it will be effective, the placebo effect, or from the treated condition resolving on its own (the natural course of disease).
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] This is further exacerbated by the tendency to turn to alternative therapies upon the failure of medicine, at which point the condition will be at its worst and most likely to spontaneously improve.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In the absence of this bias, especially for diseases that are not expected to get better by themselves such as cancer or HIV infection, multiple studies have shown significantly worse outcomes if patients turn to alternative therapies.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] While this may be because these patients avoid effective treatment, some alternative therapies are actively harmful (such as cyanide poisoning from amygdalin, or the intentional ingestion of hydrogen peroxide) or actively interfere with effective treatments.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] The alternative medicine sector is a highly profitable industry with a strong lobby, and faces far less regulation over the use and marketing of unproven treatments.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] **Complementary medicine** (**CM**), **complementary and alternative medicine** (**CAM**), **functional medicine** (**FM**), **integrated medicine** or **integrative medicine** (**IM**), and **holistic medicine** attempt to combine alternative practices with those of mainstream medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Traditional medicine practices become "alternative" when used outside their original settings and without proper scientific explanation and evidence.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative methods are often marketed as more "natural" or "holistic" than methods offered by medical science, that is sometimes derogatorily called "Big Pharma" by supporters of alternative medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Billions of dollars have been spent studying alternative medicine, with few or no positive results and many methods thoroughly disproven.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Terminology has shifted over time, reflecting the preferred branding of practitioners.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Therapies are often framed as "natural" or "holistic", implicitly and intentionally suggesting that conventional medicine is "artificial" and "narrow in scope".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] The meaning of the term "alternative" in the expression "alternative medicine", is not that it is an effective alternative to medical science (though some alternative medicine promoters may use the loose terminology to give the appearance of effectiveness).
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] "Biomedicine" or "medicine" is that part of medical science that applies principles of biology, physiology, molecular biology, biophysics, and other natural sciences to clinical practice, using scientific methods to establish the effectiveness of that practice.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Unlike medicine, an alternative product or practice does not originate from using scientific methods, but may instead be based on hearsay, religion, tradition, superstition, belief in supernatural energies, pseudoscience, errors in reasoning, propaganda, fraud, or other unscientific sources.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Some other definitions seek to specify alternative medicine in terms of its social and political marginality to mainstream healthcare.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] This can refer to the lack of support that alternative therapies receive from medical scientists regarding access to research funding, sympathetic coverage in the medical press, or inclusion in the standard medical curriculum.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] For example, a widely used definition devised by the National Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine (NCCIH) calls it "a group of diverse medical and health care systems, practices, and products that are not generally considered part of conventional medicine".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Some mainstream academic medical centers have integrative or functional medicine departments, including the Cleveland Clinic, the Mayo Clinic, Stanford University, UCLA, UC San Francisco and Northwestern University.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In contrast, other medical practitioners are unconvinced by these practices.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] For example, surgical oncologist, David Gorski has described integrative medicine as an attempt to bring pseudoscience into academic science-based medicine with skeptics such as Gorski and David Colquhoun referring to this with the pejorative term "quackademia".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Robert Todd Carroll described integrative medicine as "a synonym for 'alternative' medicine that, at its worst, integrates sense with nonsense.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] At its best, integrative medicine supports both consensus treatments of science-based medicine and treatments that the science, while promising perhaps, does not justify." Rose Shapiro has criticized the field of alternative medicine for rebranding the same practices as integrative medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] CAM is an acronym for *complementary and alternative medicine*.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Functional medicine (FM) is a form of alternative medicine that encompasses many unproven and disproven methods and treatments.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] It is a rebranding of complementary and alternative medicine (CAM), and as such is pseudoscientific, and has been described as a form of quackery.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In the US, FM practices have been ruled ineligible for course credits by the American Academy of Family Physicians because of concerns they may be harmful.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Functional medicine was created by Jeffrey Bland, who founded The Institute for Functional Medicine (IFM), which is based in the US state of Washington, in the early 1990s as part of one of his companies, HealthComm.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] IFM, which promotes functional medicine, became a registered non-profit in 2001.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Mark Hyman became an IFM board member and prominent promoter.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] David Gorski, a surgical oncologist at Wayne State University, has written that FM is not well-defined and performs "expensive and generally unnecessary tests".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Gorski says FM's vagueness is a deliberate tactic that makes functional medicine difficult to challenge.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] These are meant to correspond to the underlying causes of health issues, the immediate causes, and the particular characteristics of a person's illness.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] A functional medicine practitioner devises a "matrix" from these factors to serve as the basis for treatment.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Treatments, practices, and concepts are generally not supported by medical evidence.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Patients of functional medicine practitioners may also be told to undertake unnecessary diets that can limit food choices.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In the 1990s, integrative medicine started to be marketed by a new term, "functional medicine".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] FM practitioners claim to diagnose and treat conditions that have been found by research studies not to exist, such as adrenal fatigue and numerous imbalances in body chemistry.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] For instance, contrary to scientific evidence, Joe Pizzorno, a major figure in FM, claimed that 25% of people in the United States have heavy metal poisoning and need to undergo detoxification.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Many scientists state that such detox supplements are a waste of time and money.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Detox has been also called "mass delusion".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In 2014, the American Academy of Family Physicians withdrew course credits for functional medicine courses, having identified some of its treatments as "harmful and dangerous".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In 2018, it partly lifted the ban, but only to allow overview classes, not to teach its practice.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] The opening of centers for functional medicine at the Cleveland Clinic and George Washington University was described by David Gorski as an "unfortunate" example of "quackademia" — that is, a quackery infiltrating academic medical centers.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Traditional medicine (TM) refers to certain practices within a culture which have existed since before the advent of medical science, Many TM practices are based on "holistic" approaches to disease and health, versus the scientific evidence-based methods in conventional medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Others say that alternative medicine cannot be precisely defined because of the diversity of theories and practices it includes, and because the boundaries between alternative and conventional medicine overlap, are porous, and change.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Healthcare practices categorized as alternative may differ in their historical origin, theoretical basis, diagnostic technique, therapeutic practice and in their relationship to the medical mainstream.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Under a definition of alternative medicine as "non-mainstream", treatments considered alternative in one location may be considered conventional in another.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] There's only medicine that works and medicine that doesn't.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine consists of a wide range of health care practices, products, and therapies.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] The shared feature is a claim to heal that is not based on the scientific method.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine practices are diverse in their foundations and methodologies.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine practices may be classified by their cultural origins or by the types of beliefs upon which they are based.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Different cultures may have their own unique traditional or belief based practices developed recently or over thousands of years, and specific practices or entire systems of practices.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine, such as using naturopathy or homeopathy in place of conventional medicine, is based on belief systems not grounded in science.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medical systems may be based on traditional medicine practices, such as traditional Chinese medicine (TCM), Ayurveda in India, or practices of other cultures around the world.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Some useful applications of traditional medicines have been researched and accepted within ordinary medicine, however the underlying belief systems are seldom scientific and are not accepted.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Bases of belief may include belief in existence of supernatural energies undetected by the science of physics, as in biofields, or in belief in properties of the energies of physics that are inconsistent with the laws of physics, as in energy medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Substance based practices use substances found in nature such as herbs, foods, non-vitamin supplements and megavitamins, animal and fungal products, and minerals, including use of these products in traditional medical practices that may also incorporate other methods.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Examples include healing claims for non-vitamin supplements, fish oil, Omega-3 fatty acid, glucosamine, echinacea, flaxseed oil, and ginseng.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Herbal medicine, or phytotherapy, includes not just the use of plant products, but may also include the use of animal and mineral products.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] It is among the most commercially successful branches of alternative medicine, and includes the tablets, powders and elixirs that are sold as "nutritional supplements".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Only a very small percentage of these have been shown to have any efficacy, and there is little regulation as to standards and safety of their contents.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] The United States agency National Center for Complementary and Integrative Health (NCCIH) has created a classification system for branches of complementary and alternative medicine that divides them into five major groups.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] These groups have some overlap, and distinguish two types of energy medicine: *veritable* which involves scientifically observable energy (including magnet therapy, colorpuncture and light therapy) and *putative*, which invokes physically undetectable or unverifiable energy.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] None of these energies have any evidence to support that they affect the body in any positive or health promoting way.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Mind-body interventions: Explore the interconnection between the mind, body, and spirit, under the premise that they affect "bodily functions and symptoms".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] A connection between mind and body is conventional medical fact, and this classification does not include therapies with proven function such as cognitive behavioral therapy.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] "Biology"-based practices: Use substances found in nature such as herbs, foods, vitamins, and other natural substances.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] (As used here, "biology" does *not* refer to the science of biology, but is a usage newly coined by NCCIH in the primary source used for this article.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Manipulative and body-based practices: feature manipulation or movement of body parts, such as is done in bodywork, chiropractic, and osteopathic manipulation.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] It includes the histories of complementary medicine and of integrative medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Before the 1970s, western practitioners that were not part of the increasingly science-based medical establishment were referred to "irregular practitioners", and were dismissed by the medical establishment as unscientific and as practicing quackery.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Until the 1970s, irregular practice became increasingly marginalized as quackery and fraud, as western medicine increasingly incorporated scientific methods and discoveries, and had a corresponding increase in success of its treatments.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In the 1970s, irregular practices were grouped with traditional practices of nonwestern cultures and with other unproven or disproven practices that were not part of biomedicine, with the entire group collectively marketed and promoted under the single expression "alternative medicine".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Use of alternative medicine in the west began to rise following the counterculture movement of the 1960s, as part of the rising new age movement of the 1970s.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] At the same time, in 1975, the American Medical Association, which played the central role in fighting quackery in the United States, abolished its quackery committee and closed down its Department of Investigation.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] By the early to mid 1970s the expression "alternative medicine" came into widespread use, and the expression became mass marketed as a collection of "natural" and effective treatment "alternatives" to science-based biomedicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Changes included relaxed medical licensing, the development of managed care, rising consumerism, and the establishment of the USA Office of Alternative Medicine (later National Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine, currently National Center for Complementary and Integrative Health).
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Mainly as a result of reforms following the Flexner Report of 1910 medical education in established medical schools in the US has generally not included alternative medicine as a teaching topic.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Typically, their teaching is based on current practice and scientific knowledge about: anatomy, physiology, histology, embryology, neuroanatomy, pathology, pharmacology, microbiology and immunology.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Medical schools' teaching includes such topics as doctor-patient communication, ethics, the art of medicine, and engaging in complex clinical reasoning (medical decision-making).
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Writing in 2002, Snyderman and Weil remarked that by the early twentieth century the Flexner model had helped to create the 20th-century academic health center, in which education, research, and practice were inseparable.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] By 2001 some form of CAM training was being offered by at least 75 out of 125 medical schools in the US.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Exceptionally, the School of Medicine of the University of Maryland, Baltimore, includes a research institute for integrative medicine (a member entity of the Cochrane Collaboration).
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Medical schools are responsible for conferring medical degrees, but a physician typically may not legally practice medicine until licensed by the local government authority.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Licensed physicians in the US who have attended one of the established medical schools there have usually graduated Doctor of Medicine (MD).
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] All states require that applicants for MD licensure be graduates of an approved medical school and complete the United States Medical Licensing Examination (USMLE).
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] There is a general scientific consensus that alternative therapies lack the requisite scientific validation, and their effectiveness is either unproved or disproved.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Many of the claims regarding the efficacy of alternative medicines are controversial, since research on them is frequently of low quality and methodologically flawed.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Selective publication bias, marked differences in product quality and standardisation, and some companies making unsubstantiated claims call into question the claims of efficacy of isolated examples where there is evidence for alternative therapies.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In 2003, a project funded by the CDC identified 208 condition-treatment pairs, of which 58% had been studied by at least one randomized controlled trial (RCT), and 23% had been assessed with a meta-analysis.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] According to a 2005 book by a US Institute of Medicine panel, the number of RCTs focused on CAM has risen dramatically.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] As of 2005, the Cochrane Library had 145 CAM-related Cochrane systematic reviews and 340 non-Cochrane systematic reviews.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] An analysis of the conclusions of only the 145 Cochrane reviews was done by two readers.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In 83% of the cases, the readers agreed.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In the 17% in which they disagreed, a third reader agreed with one of the initial readers to set a rating.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] These studies found that, for CAM, 38.4% concluded positive effect or possibly positive (12.4%), 4.8% concluded no effect, 0.7% concluded harmful effect, and 56.6% concluded insufficient evidence.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] An assessment of conventional treatments found that 41.3% concluded positive or possibly positive effect, 20% concluded no effect, 8.1% concluded net harmful effects, and 21.3% concluded insufficient evidence.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] However, the CAM review used the more developed 2004 Cochrane database, while the conventional review used the initial 1998 Cochrane database.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative therapies do not "complement" (improve the effect of, or mitigate the side effects of) functional medical treatment.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Significant drug interactions caused by alternative therapies may instead negatively impact functional treatment by making prescription drugs less effective, such as interference by herbal preparations with warfarin.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In the same way as for conventional therapies, drugs, and interventions, it can be difficult to test the efficacy of alternative medicine in clinical trials.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In instances where an established, effective, treatment for a condition is already available, the Helsinki Declaration states that withholding such treatment is unethical in most circumstances.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Use of standard-of-care treatment in addition to an alternative technique being tested may produce confounded or difficult-to-interpret results.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Anything classified as alternative medicine by definition does not have a proven healing or medical effect.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] However, there are different mechanisms through which it can be perceived to "work".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] The common denominator of these mechanisms is that effects are mis-attributed to the alternative treatment.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] A placebo is a treatment with no intended therapeutic value.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] An example of a placebo is an inert pill, but it can include more dramatic interventions like sham surgery.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] The *placebo effect* is the concept that patients will perceive an improvement after being treated with an inert treatment.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] The opposite of the placebo effect is the *nocebo effect*, when patients who expect a treatment to be harmful will perceive harmful effects after taking it.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Placebos do not have a physical effect on diseases or improve overall outcomes, but patients may report improvements in subjective outcomes such as pain and nausea.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] A 1955 study suggested that a substantial part of a medicine's impact was due to the placebo effect.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] However, reassessments found the study to have flawed methodology.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] This and other modern reviews suggest that other factors like natural recovery and reporting bias should also be considered.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] All of these are reasons why alternative therapies may be credited for improving a patient's condition even though the objective effect is non-existent, or even harmful.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] David Gorski argues that alternative treatments should be treated as a placebo, rather than as medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Almost none have performed significantly better than a placebo in clinical trials.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Furthermore, distrust of conventional medicine may lead to patients experiencing the nocebo effect when taking effective medication.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] A patient who receives an inert treatment may report improvements afterwards that it did not cause.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] Assuming it was the cause without evidence is an example of the regression fallacy.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] This may be due to a natural recovery from the illness, or a fluctuation in the symptoms of a long-term condition.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] The concept of regression toward the mean implies that an extreme result is more likely to be followed by a less extreme result.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] There are also reasons why a placebo treatment group may outperform a "no-treatment" group in a test which are not related to a patient's experience.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] These include patients reporting more favourable results than they really felt due to politeness or "experimental subordination", observer bias, and misleading wording of questions.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p01] In their 2010 systematic review of studies into placebos, Asbjørn Hróbjartsson and Peter C.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Practitioners of complementary medicine usually discuss and advise patients as to available alternative therapies.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Patients often express interest in mind-body complementary therapies because they offer a non-drug approach to treating some health conditions.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In a 2018 interview with *The BMJ*, Edzard Ernst stated: "The present popularity of complementary and alternative medicine is also inviting criticism of what we are doing in mainstream medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] It shows that we aren't fulfilling a certain need-we are not giving patients enough time, compassion, or empathy.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] These are things that complementary practitioners are very good at.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine is a profitable industry with large media advertising expenditures.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Accordingly, alternative practices are often portrayed positively and compared favorably to "big pharma".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Paul Offit proposed that "alternative medicine becomes quackery" in four ways: by recommending against conventional therapies that are helpful, promoting potentially harmful therapies without adequate warning, draining patients' bank accounts, or by promoting "magical thinking".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Promoting alternative medicine has been called dangerous and unethical.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Authors have speculated on the socio-cultural and psychological reasons for the appeal of alternative medicines among the minority using them *in lieu* of conventional medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] There are several socio-cultural reasons for the interest in these treatments centered on the low level of scientific literacy among the public at large and a concomitant increase in antiscientific attitudes and new age mysticism.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Related to this are vigorous marketing of extravagant claims by the alternative medical community combined with inadequate media scrutiny and attacks on critics.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine is criticized for taking advantage of the least fortunate members of society.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Many patients lack access to contemporary medicine, due to a lack of private or public health insurance, which leads them to seek out lower-cost alternative medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Medical doctors are also aggressively marketing alternative medicine to profit from this market.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Patients can be averse to the painful, unpleasant, and sometimes-dangerous side effects of biomedical treatments.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Treatments for severe diseases such as cancer and HIV infection have well-known, significant side-effects.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Even low-risk medications such as antibiotics can have potential to cause life-threatening anaphylactic reactions in a very few individuals.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Many medications may cause minor but bothersome symptoms such as cough or upset stomach.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In all of these cases, patients may be seeking out alternative therapies to avoid the adverse effects of conventional treatments.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] According to research published in 2015, the increasing popularity of CAM needs to be explained by moral convictions or lifestyle choices rather than by economic reasoning.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In developing nations, access to essential medicines is severely restricted by lack of resources and poverty.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Traditional remedies, often closely resembling or forming the basis for alternative remedies, may comprise primary healthcare or be integrated into the healthcare system.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In Africa, traditional medicine is used for 80% of primary healthcare, and in developing nations as a whole over one-third of the population lack access to essential medicines.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In Latin America, inequities against BIPOC communities keep them tied to their traditional practices and therefore, it is often these communities that constitute the majority of users of alternative medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Racist attitudes towards certain communities disable them from accessing more urbanized modes of care.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In a study that assessed access to care in rural communities of Latin America, it was found that discrimination is a huge barrier to the ability of citizens to access care; more specifically, women of Indigenous and African descent, and lower-income families were especially hurt.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Such exclusion exacerbates the inequities that minorities in Latin America already face.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Consistently excluded from many systems of westernized care for socioeconomic and other reasons, low-income communities of color often turn to traditional medicine for care as it has proved reliable to them across generations.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Commentators including David Horrobin have proposed adopting a prize system to reward medical research.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] This stands in opposition to the current mechanism for funding research proposals in most countries around the world.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In the US, the NCCIH provides public research funding for alternative medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] The NCCIH has spent more than US$2.5 billion on such research since 1992 and this research has not demonstrated the efficacy of alternative therapies.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] As of 2011, the NCCIH's sister organization in the NIH Office of Cancer Complementary and Alternative Medicine had given out grants of around $105 million each year for several years.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Testing alternative medicine that has no scientific basis (as in the aforementioned grants) has been called a waste of scarce research resources.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] That alternative medicine has been on the rise "in countries where Western science and scientific method generally are accepted as the major foundations for healthcare, and 'evidence-based' practice is the dominant paradigm" was described as an "enigma" in the *Medical Journal of Australia*.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] A 15-year systematic review published in 2022 on the global acceptance and use of CAM among medical specialists found the overall acceptance of CAM at 52% and the overall use at 45%.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In the United States, the 1974 Child Abuse Prevention and Treatment Act (CAPTA) required that for states to receive federal money, they had to grant religious exemptions to child neglect and abuse laws regarding religion-based healing practices.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Thirty-one states have child-abuse religious exemptions.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] The use of alternative medicine in the US has increased, with a 50 percent increase in expenditures and a 25 percent increase in the use of alternative therapies between 1990 and 1997 in America.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] According to a national survey conducted in 2002, "36 percent of U.S. adults aged 18 years and over use some form of complementary and alternative medicine." Americans spend many billions on the therapies annually.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Most Americans used CAM to treat and/or prevent musculoskeletal conditions or other conditions associated with chronic or recurring pain.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In America, women were more likely than men to use CAM, with the biggest difference in use of mind-body therapies including prayer specifically for health reasons".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In 2008, more than 37% of American hospitals offered alternative therapies, up from 27 percent in 2005, and 25% in 2004.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] More than 70% of the hospitals offering CAM were in urban areas.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] A survey of Americans found that 88 percent thought that "there are some good ways of treating sickness that medical science does not recognize".
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Use of magnets was the most common tool in energy medicine in America, and among users of it, 58 percent described it as at least "sort of scientific", when it is not at all scientific.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In 2002, at least 60 percent of US medical schools have at least some class time spent teaching alternative therapies.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] "Therapeutic touch" was taught at more than 100 colleges and universities in 75 countries before the practice was debunked by a nine-year-old child for a school science project.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] The most common CAM therapies used in the US in 2002 were prayer (45%), herbalism (19%), breathing meditation (12%), meditation (8%), chiropractic medicine (8%), yoga (5–6%), body work (5%), diet-based therapy (4%), progressive relaxation (3%), mega-vitamin therapy (3%) and visualization (2%).
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In Britain, the most often used alternative therapies were Alexander technique, aromatherapy, Bach and other flower remedies, body work therapies including massage, Counseling stress therapies, hypnotherapy, meditation, reflexology, Shiatsu, Ayurvedic medicine, nutritional medicine, and yoga.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Ayurvedic medicine remedies are mainly plant based with some use of animal materials.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Safety concerns include the use of herbs containing toxic compounds and the lack of quality control in Ayurvedic facilities.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] According to the National Health Service (England), the most commonly used complementary and alternative medicines (CAM) supported by the NHS in the UK are: acupuncture, aromatherapy, chiropractic, homeopathy, massage, osteopathy and clinical hypnotherapy.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Complementary therapies are often used in palliative care or by practitioners attempting to manage chronic pain in patients.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Integrative medicine is considered more acceptable in the interdisciplinary approach used in palliative care than in other areas of medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] "From its early experiences of care for the dying, palliative care took for granted the necessity of placing patient values and lifestyle habits at the core of any design and delivery of quality care at the end of life.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] The alternative medicine lobby has successfully pushed for alternative therapies to be subject to far less regulation than conventional medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Some professions of complementary/traditional/alternative medicine, such as chiropractic, have achieved full regulation in North America and other parts of the world and are regulated in a manner similar to that governing science-based medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In contrast, other approaches may be partially recognized and others have no regulation at all.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In some cases, promotion of alternative therapies is allowed when there is demonstrably no effect, only a tradition of use.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Despite laws making it illegal to market or promote alternative therapies for use in cancer treatment, many practitioners promote them.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Regulation and licensing of alternative medicine ranges widely from country to country, and state to state.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In Austria and Germany complementary and alternative medicine is mainly in the hands of doctors with MDs, and half or more of the American alternative practitioners are licensed MDs.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In Germany herbs are tightly regulated: half are prescribed by doctors and covered by health insurance.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Government bodies in the US and elsewhere have published information or guidance about alternative medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Food and Drug Administration (FDA), has issued online warnings for consumers about medication health fraud.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] This includes a section on Alternative Medicine Fraud, such as a warning that Ayurvedic products generally have not been approved by the FDA before marketing.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] The National Science Foundation has studied the problematic side of the public's attitudes and understandings of science fiction, pseudoscience, and belief in alternative medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Forms of alternative medicine that are biologically active can be dangerous even when used in conjunction with conventional medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Examples include immuno-augmentation therapy, shark cartilage, bioresonance therapy, oxygen and ozone therapies, and insulin potentiation therapy.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Some herbal remedies can cause dangerous interactions with chemotherapy drugs, radiation therapy, or anesthetics during surgery, among other problems.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Conventional treatments are subjected to testing for undesired side-effects, whereas alternative therapies, in general, are not subjected to such testing at all.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Any treatment – whether conventional or alternative – that has a biological or psychological effect on a patient may also have potential to possess dangerous biological or psychological side-effects.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] An exception to the normal thinking regarding side-effects is homeopathy.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine may discourage people from getting the best possible treatment.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Those having experienced or perceived success with one alternative therapy for a minor ailment may be convinced of its efficacy and persuaded to extrapolate that success to some other alternative therapy for a more serious, possibly life-threatening illness.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] For this reason, critics argue that therapies that rely on the placebo effect to define success are very dangerous.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] According to mental health journalist Scott Lilienfeld in 2002, "unvalidated or scientifically unsupported mental health practices can lead individuals to forgo effective treatments" and refers to this as opportunity cost.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Individuals who spend large amounts of time and money on ineffective treatments may be left with precious little of either, and may forfeit the opportunity to obtain treatments that could be more helpful.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In short, even innocuous treatments can indirectly produce negative outcomes.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Between 2001 and 2003, four children died in Australia because their parents chose ineffective naturopathic, homeopathic, or other alternative medicines and diets rather than conventional therapies.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] There have always been "many therapies offered outside of conventional cancer treatment centers and based on theories not found in biomedicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Complementary and alternative medicine (CAM) is not as well researched as conventional medicine, which undergoes intense research before release to the public.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Practitioners of science-based medicine also discard practices and treatments when they are shown ineffective, while alternative practitioners do not.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Funding for research is also sparse making it difficult to do further research for effectiveness of CAM.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Most funding for CAM is funded by government agencies.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Proposed research for CAM are rejected by most private funding agencies because the results of research are not reliable.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] The research for CAM has to meet certain standards from research ethics committees, which most CAM researchers find almost impossible to meet.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Even with the little research done on it, CAM has not been proven to be effective.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Studies that have been done will be cited by CAM practitioners in an attempt to claim a basis in science.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] These studies tend to have a variety of problems, such as small samples, various biases, poor research design, lack of controls, negative results, etc.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Even those with positive results can be better explained as resulting in false positives due to bias and noisy data.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine may lead to a false understanding of the body and of the process of science.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] It is possible for a method to change categories (proven vs. unproven), based on increased knowledge of its effectiveness or lack thereof.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Prominent supporters of this position are George D.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Lundberg, former editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* (*JAMA*) and the journal's interim editor-in-chief Phil Fontanarosa.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Writing in 1999 in *CA: A Cancer Journal for Clinicians* Barrie R.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Cassileth mentioned a 1997 letter to the United States Senate's Subcommittee on Public Health and Safety, which had deplored the lack of critical thinking and scientific rigor in OAM-supported research, had been signed by four Nobel Laureates and other prominent scientists.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Sampson has also pointed out that CAM tolerated contradiction without thorough reason and experiment.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Barrett has pointed out that there is a policy at the NIH of never saying something does not work, only that a different version or dose might give different results.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Barrett also expressed concern that, just because some "alternatives" have merit, there is the impression that the rest deserve equal consideration and respect even though most are worthless, since they are all classified under the one heading of alternative medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Many alternative medical treatments are not patentable, which may lead to less research funding from the private sector.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In addition, in most countries, alternative therapies (in contrast to pharmaceuticals) can be marketed without any proof of efficacy – also a disincentive for manufacturers to fund scientific research.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] CAM is also often less regulated than conventional medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] There are ethical concerns about whether people who perform CAM have the proper knowledge to treat patients.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] CAM is often done by non-physicians who do not operate with the same medical licensing laws which govern conventional medicine, and it is often described as an issue of non-maleficence.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] According to two writers, Wallace Sampson and K.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Butler, marketing is part of the training required in alternative medicine, and propaganda methods in alternative medicine have been traced back to those used by Hitler and Goebbels in their promotion of pseudoscience in medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] In November 2011 Edzard Ernst stated that the "level of misinformation about alternative medicine has now reached the point where it has become dangerous and unethical.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] So far, alternative medicine has remained an ethics-free zone.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Some commentators have said that special consideration must be given to the issue of conflicts of interest in alternative medicine.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Edzard Ernst has said that most researchers into alternative medicine are at risk of "unidirectional bias" because of a generally uncritical belief in their chosen subject.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Ernst cites as evidence the phenomenon whereby 100% of a sample of acupuncture trials originating in China had positive conclusions.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] David Gorski contrasts evidence-based medicine, in which researchers try to disprove hyphotheses, with what he says is the frequent practice in pseudoscience-based research, of striving to confirm pre-existing notions.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Research into alternative therapies has been criticized for "diverting research time, money, and other resources from more fruitful lines of investigation in order to pursue a theory that has no basis in biology." Research methods expert and author of *Snake Oil Science*, R.
[src:bruise/alternative-medicine-p02] Barker Bausell, has stated that "it's become politically correct to investigate nonsense." A commonly cited statistic is that the US National Institute of Health had spent $2.5 billion on investigating alternative therapies prior to 2009, with none being found to be effective.
[src:bruise/bruise] A **bruise**, also known as a **contusion**, is a type of hematoma of tissue, the most common cause being capillaries damaged by trauma, causing localized bleeding that extravasates into the surrounding interstitial tissues.
[src:bruise/bruise] Most bruises occur close enough to the epidermis such that the bleeding causes a visible discoloration.
[src:bruise/bruise] The bruise then remains visible until the blood is either absorbed by tissues or cleared by immune system action.
[src:bruise/bruise] Bruises which do not blanch under pressure can involve capillaries at the level of skin, subcutaneous tissue, muscle, or bone.
[src:bruise/bruise] Bruises are not to be confused with other similar-looking lesions.
[src:bruise/bruise] As a type of hematoma, a bruise is always caused by internal bleeding into the interstitial tissues which does not break through the skin, usually initiated by blunt trauma, which causes damage through physical compression and deceleration forces.
[src:bruise/bruise] Trauma sufficient to cause bruising can occur from a wide variety of situations including accidents, falls, and surgeries.
[src:bruise/bruise] Disease states such as insufficient or malfunctioning platelets, other coagulation deficiencies, or vascular disorders, such as venous blockage associated with severe allergies can lead to the formation of purpura which is not to be confused with trauma-related bruising/contusion.
[src:bruise/bruise] If the trauma is sufficient to break the skin and allow blood to escape the interstitial tissues, the injury is not a bruise but bleeding, a different variety of hemorrhage.
[src:bruise/bruise] Such injuries may be accompanied by bruising elsewhere.
[src:bruise/bruise] Bruises often induce pain immediately after the trauma that results in their formation, but small bruises are not normally dangerous alone.
[src:bruise/bruise] Sometimes bruises can be serious, leading to other more life-threatening forms of hematoma, such as when associated with serious injuries, including fractures and more severe internal bleeding.
[src:bruise/bruise] The likelihood and severity of bruising depends on many factors, including type and healthiness of affected tissues.
[src:bruise/bruise] Minor bruises may be easily recognized in people with light skin color by characteristic blue or purple appearance (idiomatically described as "black and blue") in the days following the injury.
[src:bruise/bruise] By definition, ecchymoses are 1 centimetres in size or larger, and are therefore larger than petechiae (less than 3 millimetres in diameter) or purpura (3 to 10 millimetres in diameter).
[src:bruise/bruise] Ecchymoses also have a more diffuse border than other purpura.
[src:bruise/bruise] A broader definition of ecchymosis is the escape of blood into the tissues from ruptured blood vessels.
[src:bruise/bruise] The term also applies to the subcutaneous discoloration resulting from seepage of blood within the injured tissue.
[src:bruise/bruise] Bruise colors vary from red, blue, or almost black, depending on the severity of broken capillaries or blood vessels within the bruise site.
[src:bruise/bruise] Broken venules or arterioles often result in a deep blue or dark red bruise, respectively.
[src:bruise/bruise] Darker colored bruises may result from a more severe bleeding from both blood vessels.
[src:bruise/bruise] Older bruises may appear yellow, green or brown.
[src:bruise/bruise] There are many causes of subcutaneous hematomas including ecchymoses.
[src:bruise/bruise] Coagulopathies such as hemophilia A may cause ecchymosis formation in children.
[src:bruise/bruise] The medication betamethasone can have the adverse effect of causing ecchymosis.
[src:bruise/bruise] The presence of bruises may be seen in patients with platelet or coagulation disorders, or those who are being treated with an anticoagulant.
[src:bruise/bruise] Unexplained bruising may be a warning sign of child abuse, domestic abuse, hard blows during fighting sports, or serious medical problems such as leukemia or meningoccocal infection.
[src:bruise/bruise] Unexplained bruising can also indicate internal bleeding or certain types of cancer.
[src:bruise/bruise] Long-term glucocorticoid therapy can cause easy bruising.
[src:bruise/bruise] Bruising present around the navel (belly button) with severe abdominal pain suggests acute pancreatitis.
[src:bruise/bruise] Connective tissue disorders such as Ehlers–Danlos syndrome may cause relatively easy or spontaneous bruising depending on the severity.
[src:bruise/bruise] Spontaneous bruising or bruising with minimal trauma in the absence of other explanations and together with other minor or major criteria suggestive of vascular Ehlers–Danlos Syndrome (vEDS) suggests genetic testing for the condition.
[src:bruise/bruise] During an autopsy, bruises accompanying abrasions indicate the abrasions occurred while the individual was alive, as opposed to damage incurred post mortem.
[src:bruise/bruise] Bruise shapes may correspond directly to the instrument of injury or be modified by additional factors.
[src:bruise/bruise] Bruises often become more prominent as time lapses, resulting in additional size and swelling, and may grow to a large size over the course of the hours after the injury that caused the bruise was inflicted.
[src:bruise/bruise] Bruises can be scored on a scale from 0–5 to categorize the severity and danger of the injury.
[src:bruise/bruise] The harm score is determined by the extent and severity of the injuries to the organs and tissues causing the bruising, in turn depending on multiple factors.
[src:bruise/bruise] For example, a contracted muscle will bruise more severely, as will tissues crushed against underlying bone.
[src:bruise/bruise] Capillaries vary in strength, stiffness and toughness, which can also vary by age and medical conditions.
[src:bruise/bruise] Low levels of damaging forces produce small bruises and generally cause the individual to feel minor pain straight away.
[src:bruise/bruise] Repeated impacts worsen bruises, increasing the harm level.
[src:bruise/bruise] Normally, light bruises heal nearly completely within two weeks, although duration is affected by variation in severity and individual healing processes; generally, more severe or deeper bruises take somewhat longer.
[src:bruise/bruise] Severe bruising (harm score 2–3) may be dangerous or cause serious complications.
[src:bruise/bruise] Further bleeding and excess fluid may accumulate causing a hard, fluctuating lump or swelling hematoma.
[src:bruise/bruise] This has the potential to cause compartment syndrome in which the swelling cuts off blood flow to the tissues.
[src:bruise/bruise] The trauma that induced the bruise may also have caused other severe and potentially fatal harm to internal organs.
[src:bruise/bruise] For example, impacts to the head can cause traumatic brain injury: bleeding, bruising and massive swelling of the brain with the potential to cause concussion, coma and death.
[src:bruise/bruise] Treatment for brain bruising may involve emergency surgery to relieve the pressure on the brain.
[src:bruise/bruise] Damage that causes bruising can also cause bones to be broken, tendons or muscles to be strained, ligaments to be sprained, or other tissue to be damaged.
[src:bruise/bruise] The symptoms and signs of these injuries may initially appear to be those of simple bruising.
[src:bruise/bruise] Abdominal bruising or severe injuries that cause difficulty in moving a limb or the feeling of liquid under the skin may indicate life-threatening injury and require the attention of a physician.
[src:bruise/bruise] Increased distress to tissue causes capillaries to break under the skin, allowing blood to escape and build up.
[src:bruise/bruise] As time progresses, blood seeps into the surrounding tissues, causing the bruise to darken and spread.
[src:bruise/bruise] Nerve endings within the affected tissue detect the increased pressure, which, depending on severity and location, may be perceived as pain or pressure or be asymptomatic.
[src:bruise/bruise] The damaged capillary endothelium releases endothelin, a hormone that causes narrowing of the blood vessel to minimize bleeding.
[src:bruise/bruise] As the endothelium is destroyed, the underlying von Willebrand factor is exposed and initiates coagulation, which creates a temporary clot to plug the wound and eventually leads to restoration of normal tissue.
[src:bruise/bruise] During this time, larger bruises may change color due to the breakdown of hemoglobin from within escaped red blood cells in the extracellular space.
[src:bruise/bruise] As these products are cleared from the area, the bruise disappears.
[src:bruise/bruise] Often the underlying tissue damage has been repaired long before this process is complete.
[src:bruise/bruise] Treatment for light bruises is minimal and may include RICE (rest, ice, compression, and elevation), painkillers (particularly NSAIDs) and, later in recovery, light stretching exercises.
[src:bruise/bruise] Particularly, immediate application of ice while elevating the area may reduce or completely prevent swelling by restricting blood flow to the area and preventing internal bleeding.
[src:bruise/bruise] Rest and preventing re-injury is essential for rapid recovery.
[src:bruise/bruise] Very gently massaging the area and applying heat may encourage blood flow and relieve pain according to the gate control theory of pain, although causing additional pain may indicate the massage is exacerbating the injury.
[src:bruise/bruise] Folk medicine, including ancient medicine of Egyptians, Greeks, Celts, Turks, Slavs, Maya, Aztecs and Chinese, has used bruising as a treatment for some health problems.
[src:bruise/bruise] The methods vary widely and include cupping, scraping, and slapping.
[src:bruise/bruise] Fire cupping uses suction which causes bruising in patients.
[src:bruise/bruise] Scraping (gua sha) uses a small hand device with a rounded edge to gently scrape the scalp or the skin.
[src:bruise/bruise] Another ancient device that creates mild bruising is a strigil, used by Greeks and Romans in the bath.
[src:bruise/bruise] Archaeologically there is no precedent for scraping tools before Greek archaeological evidence, not Chinese or Egyptian.
[src:bruise/bruise] The word *ecchymosis* (/ˌɛkɪˈmoʊsɪs/; plural *ecchymoses*, /ˌɛkɪˈmoʊsiːs/), comes to English from Neo-Latin, based on Greek ἐκχύμωσις, *ekchymōsis*, from ἐκχυμοῦσθαι, *ekchymousthai*, 'to extravasate blood', from ἐκ-, *ek-* (elided to ἐ-, *e-*) and χυμός, *chymos*, 'juice'.
[src:bruise/bruise] Compare *enchyma*, "tissue infused with organic juice"; elaboration from chyme, the formative juice of tissues.
